I finally reproduced this problem. It only happens with JDK 1.4. I believe
it is related with signal handlers. Here is a testcase that GPFs:

import org.eclipse.swt.internal.motif.*;
public class ProgramTest {
public static void main(String[] args) {
	try {
		System.loadLibrary("swt-kde-motif-2029");
	} catch (Throwable e) {
		return;
	}

	/* Use the character encoding for the default locale */
	byte [] nameBuffer = {(byte)'S', (byte)'W', (byte)'T',  '\0'};
	int qcString = KDE.QCString_new( nameBuffer );
	System.err.println(KDE.KApplication_new( qcString ));
	KDE.QCString_delete( qcString );
	KDE.KMimeType_allMimeTypes();
	System.out.println("done");
}
}

